The working week should be shorter and workers should have a longer weekend. Do you agree or disagree?

It has been argued that the working week has too many work days and too few weekend days. I largely agree with this proposal, while also acknowledging that the work-rest balance should reflect economic realities.

To my mind, it is the trend of history that working days should gradually diminish as the means of production advances. Indeed, work is only a means of subsistence for most people, not life itself, and it is only right that working people should enjoy the fruit of progress in technologies, such as AI, robotics, and automation, most notably by reducing the work days and spending more quality time enjoying themselves -- with families and friends, on a trip, or reading books -- the possibilities are endless. This trend is evidenced, for example, when Saturday was officially recognized as a weekend day in China in the 1990s, and I see no reason why the same trend cannot continue.

On the other hand, it is also naive to ignore the economic conditions on the ground of each country when making such far-reaching decisions as reducing the work days in a week. One must be fully aware that radically cutting work days may lead to a decrease in production output, under-employment, and other unforeseen social upheavals. Therefore meticulous care must be taken to ensure accurate measurement and analysis before going forward with a new national work-rest balance.

To conclude, I look forward with optimism to a 3-holiday week provided the decision is made after a thorough study of the macro-economic conditions. 
